PROJECT TITLE: Impression formation of mental health clients
2019-2020 Undergraduate final year independent research project

Researchers (final year psychology students): 
Ellie Thomas-Williams 
Harrison Jones

Supervisor: 
Dr Gabriela M. Jiga-Boy (G.Jiga@swansea.ac.uk)


RESEARCH QUESTIONS, HYPOTHESES &amp; ANALYSIS PLAN
General notes for analysis plan: 
•	All variables are centred to the mean prior to conducting regression analyses. 
•	We do not use any manipulation checks. We plan to perform statistical analyses on all participants’ data, except for data from participants who indicated that they understood specific hypotheses of this study at the suspicion probe stage. If, however, participants only provide generic hints about what the hypotheses could, should, or would be, we will not discard their data.

We are not aware of any analysis plan in the original manuscript. Hence, we have planned for the current analyses based on the little information we could collect from the paper. 

In the original paper, the following information was provided regarding the analyses: "Analyses of variance were performed to evaluate the Impact of the two variables: sex [of client], with two levels [male vs. female], and swearing [of client], with three levels [no swearing, swearing, and really swearing] on seven rating scale items for the adult client and six for the adolescent client. All comparisons in the analysis were between groups of independent subjects."

Tyler’s (1977) results for adult clients:
-	No main effect of sex;
-	Main effect of swearing on anger: Adult clients who swear (mildly or moderately) are perceived as more angry than those who do not swear;
-	Sex x swearing interaction on anger: The non-swearing and the really swearing women were rated as more angry than those swearing mildly; same effect not observed for males;
-	Sex x swearing interaction on self-control: The non-swearing and the really swearing women were rated as having less self-control than those swearing mildly; no such main effect for males;
-	No other significant effects of sex, swearing or sex x swearing interaction were reported on the client’s likeness, overall level of functioning, parent-child relationships, adjustment, or promiscuity. 

Tyler’s (1977) results for teenage clients:
-	Main effect of sex: male clients rated more angry than female clients;
-	Sex x swearing interaction on anger: Really swearing males were rated as being more angry than the really swearing females, who in fact, received the lowest score on all the variants;
-	Main effect of swearing on self-control: swearer teenagers were seen as less-disturbed [i.e. having more self-control] than non-swearers;
-	Sex x swearing interaction on self-control: the really swearing female teenager rated as less disturbed [i.e. having more self-control] than any other clients;
-	Sex x swearing interactions also on promiscuity and the overall level of functioning variable. This indicated that the really swearing female teenager was rated as less promiscuous and having a better overall functioning than all other categories (no swearing and mildly sweating male and female teenagers);
-	No other significant effects of sex, swearing or sex x swearing interaction were reported on the client’s likeness or parent-child relationships. 

In our replication attempt, we plan to test the impact of sex [of client], with two levels [male vs. female], and swearing [of client], with three levels [no swearing, swearing, and really swearing] on the eight rating scale items* for both the adult client and the adolescent client, mapping the analyses conducted by Tyler (1977) and reported above, and/or conducting better quality analyses such as multiple regressions with the rating scale items as outcome variables and the client’s sex, client’s swearing level and sex x swearing level as predictors, using appropriate contrast codes for the effects of swearing – e.g., contrast codes for comparing the conditions non swearing &amp; really swearing vs. mild swearing (adult client) and non swearing &amp; mild swearing vs. really swearing (teenage client). 

* Rating scales:
The client’s likeness: …how well-liked is this client?, from 1 = very well-liked to 5 = very little liked;

The client’s overall level of functioning: …what is the overall level of functioning of this client?, from 1 = very well functioning individual to 5 = has severe problems in this regard;

The client’s level of anger: …is the client experiencing feelings of anger?, from 1 = very little anger to 5 = very much anger;

The client’s parent-child relationships: …what are the parent-child relationships for this client?, from 1 = rather rich and well-functioning relationships to 5 = rather poor and problematic relationships;

The client’s self-control: …does the client have self-control?, from 1 = very little self-control to 5 = very high self-control;

The client’s adjustment: How well do you perceive the marital (adult) / social (teenager) adjustment of the client?, from 1 = very well adjusted to 5 = has severe adjustment problems;

The client’s immorality: …how immoral is this client?, from 1 = very immoral to 5 = very moral;

The client’s authenticity: …how genuine is this client?, from 1 = very little genuine to 5 = very genuine;

The client’s subjective SES (socio-economic status), adapted from Piff, P. K., Kraus, M. W., Côté, S., Cheng, B. H., &amp; Keltner, D. (2010). Having less, giving more: The influence of social class on prosocial behavior. Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, 99(5), 771–784. http://doi.org/10.1037/a0020092.
Think of this ladder as representing where people stand in the United Kingdom. At the top of the ladder are the people who are the best off – those who have the most money, the most education and the most respected jobs. At the bottom are the people who are the worst off – who have the least money, least education, and the least respected jobs of no job. The higher up you are on this ladder, the closer you are to the people at the very top; the lower you are, the closer you are to the people are the very bottom.
 	Where would you place the client on this ladder? Please choose a number that represents the rung where you think the client stands relative to other people in the United Kingdom.

